In terms of C++ coding, what are some best practices for collaboration? One suggestion is to follow a consistent and descriptive naming convention for variables, functions, and classes to make it easier for both programmers to understand the code. Another tip is to modularize the project into smaller components that can be worked on separately and later integrated. Lastly, using testing frameworks like Google Test can ensure code quality and catch bugs throughout the collaboration process. 
Can you provide a sample C++ code that demonstrates these best practices for collaboration? 
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
// consistent naming convention
int calculateSum(int num1, int num2) {
    return num1 + num2;
}
// modularization of project
class Rectangle {
    int width, height;
public:
    Rectangle(int w, int h) : width(w), height(h) {}
    int area() { return width * height; }
};
// use of testing framework
void testCalculateSum() {
    int result = calculateSum(2, 3);
    assert(result == 5);
}
int main() {
    // real-time collaboration
    std::string message = "Hello World!";
    std::cout << message << std::endl;

    // commenting code
    int num1 = 5; // programmer 1
    int num2 = 3; // programmer 2
    int sum = calculateSum(num1, num2); // sum of num1 and num2
    std::cout << "The sum is: " << sum << std::endl;

    // testing
    testCalculateSum();

    return 0;
}
```

